<br>
Whilst the albion army was occupied with the drakoran invasion (it was but days after King Constantine heeded the Avalonian plea for help) we had other more pressing matters nearer to home.<br>
<br>
The mids struck at first light, the albion army was still drunk and sleepy from the previous night's victory over Morgana's forces. What more they were scattered across an island many hundreds of miles away from Forest Sauvage and Castle Excalibur (alas Merlin's staff has been the property of Hibernia for many months). We have noone to blame but ourselves, the mids came the previous night, capturing many a Caer, and were left unharried. It was foolish not to expect the dawn raid. A handful of defenders that were close enough rallied but were far from enough.<br>
<br>
Albion woke up, we'd been living in a dream for too long. War councils were held, voices raised, agreements reached. The same tactic was applied, at the crack of dawn (10am to you lot) the albion forces struck the gates of Mjolnir Faste. The keep was claimed quickly, but greed was to be our downfall that day. Sending only a token force with Excalibur's Scabbard the rest of the army remained to take Thor's Hammer and Lug's Spear of Lightning when the scabbard was safely home. <br>
<br>
Alas, this was not to be - the small force was cornered at the milegate by twice its number. The minstrels sang their songs of speed but their throats were strangely dry, Odin's eye was watching and they had been cursed. It was not to be Albion's day. (*mumbles something about bugs*)  The brave paladin bearing the weight of the scabbard made it to the foot of the hill beneath our keep in Odin's Gate, but was slain before the guards could fire a shot.<br>
<br>
The Albion army tried to hold Myrddin long enough for the summoning to return Excalibur to us, but the mids grew in number and ours only shrank. We were doomed.<br>
<br>
Many would have been put off by such cruel fate, but more plans were made - an assault began in the early evening, whilst Midgard supped. Nottmoor fell, Bledmeer shortly after. The temple of Arawn brought an Arch Summoner of the Dead, and the entirety of Albion's might was brought to bear in the Jamtland mountains. A long and bloody fight won us Bledmeer, Hlidskialf and Glenlock. Times looked troubled as Hlid was recaptured whilst our attention was focused on Fensalir, but the rebellion did not last long.<br>
<br>
After twelve hours of heavy siege, and fierce battle the albion army made it to Mjolnir. The battle had taken its toll on our numbers but the enemy grew fewer and fewer by the minute. A final battlecry was yelled as we sieged Mjolnir, blasting through its doors. The relics were taken home to where they belong.<br>
<br>
For a week albion defended like lions, even the merest whisper of frontier activity raised an alarm call throughout the realm, and an army was quickly dispatched to repel the invaders. Things looked bad one evening with Boldiam, Berkstead, Renaris and Benowyc all in enemy hands, but a determined and continued assault won us back Renaris. A strike group retook Benowyc and the other two were reclaimed shortly afterwards.<br>
<br>
Thwarted for a week, Midgard hid its fury well, till one fateful morning Albion woke up to find Castle Excalibur in ruins and the relics once more within the icy home of Mjolnir. Stealth and Treachery, whilst albion slept the army had came. Of the three score or so Albion's awake, only ten were of a season able to defend. No match for the ten-score Midgard army.<br>
<br>
In the wake of this are we now, defeated by treachery where force of arms would not. But we'll not lie dormant for long - even now the war drums are sounding, the bugles call for Albion to unite and take back what is ours.<br>
<br>
